We had a day! 
@carolynaswisher

3 Part Race Recap. 
1. Swim 2.4 miles

Going into the swim I was pretty nervous. Never have been a strong swimmer but can manage to keep myself afloat. I am not fast or effective swimmer but we are working on it. I had a big goal of swimming under 2 hours which would be really slow but I was secretly just wanting to not drown and survive the swim. 2 loop course on the swim and the first loop I felt like it was never going to end. Different color bouys mean different things such as turn, keep going and finish. I had a hard time telling the different between the keep going and turn bouys as they looked very similar to my colorblind eyes. I kept thinking the end was near so I would push hard to only get to what was the next “keep going” bouy. Finally turned to start my second loop and got into a pretty nice groove of what it felt like was correct swimming. Trying to remember what my coach taught me about gliding and pulling through my hip and keeping my head down. My heart rate never got out of hand which was a delight. It was a tough swim getting hit and grabbed but I tried to stick towards the outside a bit to be able to stay out of the mosh pit. All in all I was super proud of my swim and finished at 1 hour and 30 mins which is a 2:20 pace.

Ironman Tulsa Race Recap Bike
Coming out of the water I to transition I was a bit shocked that I didn’t drown. I grabbed my bike gear ran into the changing tent and when I sat down I seen a lot of people just kind of taking their time. My competitiveness kicked In and I wanted to be in and out quick. Got my socks, shoes and helmet on and took off. I packed sunscreen in my bike gear bag but I didn’t want to waste time applying it. As I get to bike mount they had single pack sun screen so I grabbed and squirted it in my neck not knowing it was more than I thought. By the time I got on my bike my hands were blobbed with sunscreen and I was trying to spread it around and not get it all over my bike. Thought maybe if I wipe the majority of it on my leg I can spread from there. Lol kind of a fail. Any way we get out on the roads and pretty much get right into some inclines. Around my 5 my legs were feeling pretty rough for some reason. The bike is prolly my strongest discipline of the three just because I can sit there and pedal hard all day. The first big incline was coming and there was no way around it. I didn’t want to blow out to fast bc I knew I had around 100 miles left. As I get towards the top I kept telling myself the back side is going to be better, to only show up to a “false summit” right into another incline. But the back side did come and it was better. I hit 41.5 mph coming down the back side of the big hills and I was flying. I knew I needed to take advantage of the speed coming down as a handful of riders were quick to hit their brakes to slow them a bit. I get settled in pretty good and my nutrition from @thefeedme is hitting on point every time. I would take a SIS gel every 30-45 minutes and try to have a waffle around half way. I knew in the back of my mind I wanted to avg 18 mph but this is the first time Iv ridden more than 100 miles. I also knew that @imtri.ing was somewhere in front of me and I wanted so bad to catch him. I stopped once to grab my bike personal needs and refuel my bottles and gels then right back to work. I knew around 6 hours total would be putting me on pace for what could potentially be a sub 12 hour finish time.

Ironman Tulsa Run recap
Starting the day the run was the least of my worries, funny how that works. Coming off the bike Into transition 2 I was feeling blown up for sure. Out of transition I was hyped from the crowd and my first mile was around 7:30-8 minutes. I strung together maybe 2 miles and once I got to the river trail the legs were gone. I knew in the back of my mind @imtri.ing was still in front of me and after I seen his family they said he was close. I knew my body was done but I picked up the pace a bit to try and catch him. It took me to prolly mile 8-10 to actually catch him and I am glad I did. It was nice to suffer with a fellow friend. We continued to walk/run every bit our body could but I was fading faster and faster. I have to give credit where it’s due and if it wasn’t for Chris I was jumping off the next bridge I could find. I may have strung 2-3 miles together the entire run which is embarrassing but my body was far past the breaking point. I got to the point in race depression I didn’t care to finish. I was more than ready to get in the car and drive home. I will never forget how I felt in the moment. Thankfully Chris kept pushing and we would bounce off each other to continue to fight and race. Everything in my body hurt, mentally I was gone, physically I was gone! I was so thankful to see @carolynaswisher @mudlowery Drake and @jonest14 on the trail.  The last couple blocks I expressed my thankfulness to Chris about his friendship and help pushing me. I told him we could run the last bit and he said we should go one more and run from further out. I immediately took back all the nice things I said haha all in all the thing I was worried least about was the hardest thing I have ever done. What a ride!

It’s all over but the cryin! 
The hardest, most fun and most exciting day, after 13 hours and 42 minutes of non stop movement. I was worn out, pissed off, excited and thankful to hear the announcer saying Chuck Swisher, you are an Ironman. Filled with emotion I found my Queen @carolynaswisher I cried because I was so glad it was over. I’m so thankful for my friends and family that helped carry me across the finish line and could not have done it with out them. Any one want to do it again? @imtri.ing @steveablake @ibeshannonlowery @runernestorun

@route66marathon made us earn it this year. Rainy morning thought I’d be smart and park at the finish line, mile jog in the rain to the start line… Shoes and socks were soaked before the race started. First 15 miles I was feeling really solid and PR’d my half marathon at 8 min miles. About mile 16 the wheels started falling off. Rained off and on and the hills just kept getting bigger. Set a new full PR by just a couple minutes. All in all was a great time in Tulsa but I’m pretty glad it’s over. Cigars and Thanksgiving food then we train for the next one. See y’all next year @route66marathon @vexilbrand @cinchjeans @swisherbeefco @thefeedme
